tegory><gtr:grantReference>ES/F041993/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>The project, Between Borders: The Politics of Space and Identity in Colonial Assam, researches the process of identity construction in the western borderland region of northeastern India during the colonial period. The region shared its borders with Bhutan, Nepal, Tibet, China, and northern and eastern Bengal (contemporary Bangladesh) and also shared a cultural and historical memory with these areas. Using the tools of historical research, the project argues that colonial modernity ignored this pre-colonial connected history and transformed the fluid culture of this transitional space into one of fixed and rigid categories and boundaries. This was reinforced by narratives of nationalism from Assam and Bengal. Significantly, various social groups living in the borderland contested these processes, recovering local speech and writing counter histories in order to articulate their political and cultural identity as a borderland people, and attempting to transform what had become a marginal border under colonialism into a politically and culturally charged space. The concerns of the project connect it to broader questions relating to the imagination of areas and the structuring of knowledge. It also has a resonance in processes of ethnic mobilization in post decolonized north eastern India. 
